---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Squiggle from '../components/Squiggle.astro';
import stats from '../data/strava_stats.json';

const cards = [
	{ label: 'Day streak', value: stats.streak, unit: '' },
	{ label: 'in past 7 days', value: stats.milesLastWeek, unit: 'mi' },
	{ label: 'in past 7 days', value: stats.uniLapsLastWeek, unit: 'Uni laps' },
];

// Parse as local time (append time) so the date doesn't shift a day in UTC.
const updated = new Date(`${stats.updatedAt}T00:00:00`).toLocaleDateString('en-US', {
	year: 'numeric',
	month: 'long',
	day: 'numeric',
});
---

<BaseLayout>
	<div class="mx-auto flex min-h-full max-w-3xl flex-col px-4 py-12 sm:px-6">
		<div>
			<h1 class="mb-6 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
				Running
			</h1>

			<!-- divider -->
			<div class="mb-8">
				<Squiggle />
			</div>

			<!-- cards -->
			<div class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
				{
					cards.map((card) => (
						<div class="rounded-2xl border border-border bg-surface p-6 text-center">
							<div class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-accent">
								{card.value}
								<span class="ml-1 text-base font-medium text-muted">{card.unit}</span>
							</div>
							<div class="mt-2 text-sm text-muted">{card.label}</div>
						</div>
					))
				}
			</div>

			<p class="mt-3 text-right text-xs text-muted">
				Updated {updated} <a href="#footnote-1" class="align-super text-[0.7em] text-accent">[1]</a>
			</p>

			<!-- text -->
			<section class="prose mt-10">
				<p>
					I'm not naturally good at running. I've always wanted to be better,
					but I often struggle to stay committed to running.
					I'll get into the habit of going on a few runs a week, stick to it for a while,
					then I'll fall out of it when either life gets in the way, or I simply get bored.
					I recently read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/20628768-wooden-me">Wooden & Me</a>,
					by Woody Woodburn, and I was inspired by Woody's personal run streak<a href="#footnote-2" class="align-super text-[0.7em] text-accent no-underline!">[2]</a>,
					as well as Coach Wooden's teachings about discipline, to start a run streak of my own.
				</p>
				<p>
					For my streak, I chose to make my daily run something relatively easy and attainable, something
					where there is no excuse outside of laziness to not do it every day.
					There's a local school near me, and a lap around it is about 0.8 miles with a large decline and a steep hill.
					So I settled on running at least one "Uni" lap, named after the school, every day.
					On this page, you can see my running streak, my mileage over the last week, as well as how many total Uni laps
					I've run in the past week. The streak and mileage show my statistics for any runs, mostly so that when I travel
					I can keep the streak alive. But, the Uni laps are specifically how many times I've run around that school.
				</p>
				<p>
					I've found that the best way to get better at something is to do it every day, even if each individual
					effort is relatively small. The Wizard of Westwood agrees.
				</p>
				<div class="not-prose mt-6 rounded-2xl border-l-4 border-accent bg-surface p-5">
					<p class="text-muted">
						"Don't look for the big, quick improvement. Seek the small improvement one day at time. That's the only way it
						happens - and when it happens, it lasts." - John Wooden
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>
			<br>
		</div>

		<!-- footnotes -->
		<p
			id="footnote-1"
			class="mt-auto border-t border-border pt-6 text-sm text-muted"
		>
			[1] All running data on this page is pulled from the Strava API and processed by a python script that runs daily via Github Actions.
		</p>
		<p
			id="footnote-2"
			class="mt-auto border-border pt-6 text-sm text-muted"
		>
			[2] See the sidebar of Woody's <a class="text-accent underline underline-offset-2" href="https://woodywoodburn.com/">website</a> for the
			most up-to-date data about his ludicrous daily running streak.
		</p>
	</div>
</BaseLayout>
